Acquire Data

id.calls <- "1gRoL7lZlwm7sreA5F9WbPoH5su4n4iGS"
calls.temp <- read.csv(sprintf("https://docs.google.com/uc?id=%s&export=download", id.calls))

Wrangle Data

calls.temp$date <- as.Date(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$dow <- weekdays(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$month <- substr(calls.temp$date, 6, 7)

calls.type <- calls.temp %>%
  group_by(type) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(PCT = round(count/sum(count)*100,2))
calls <- subset(calls.temp, calls.temp$type == 'SUSPICIOUS')
calls.day <- calls %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarise(count = n())

first <- min(calls.day$date)
last <- max(calls.day$date)

calls.day <- calls.day %>% 
  complete(date = seq(ymd(first), 
                      ymd(last), 
                      "day")) %>%
  mutate(dow = wday(date, label = T, week_start = 1), 
         month.name = month(date, label = T, abbr = F),
         month.num = substr(date, 6,7),
         week = isoweek(date),
         day = day(date),
         year = year(date))

calls.day$count[is.na(calls.day$count)] = "0"
calls.day$count <- as.numeric(calls.day$count)

high <- as.numeric(max(calls.day$count))
low <- as.numeric(min(calls.day$count))
mean <- mean(calls.day$count)
sd <- sd(calls.day$count)

calls.day <- mutate(calls.day, 
                    week = case_when(month.name == "December" & week == 1 ~ 53,
                                     month.name == "January" & week %in% 52:53 ~ 0,
                                     TRUE ~ week),
                    category = cut(count, c(low-1, (mean-sd*3), (mean-sd*2), (mean-sd), mean, (mean+sd), (mean+sd*2), 
                                            (mean+sd*3), high+1)))

calls.day.time <- calls %>%
  group_by(dow, hour) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'dow'. You can override using the `.groups`
## argument.
calls.day.time <- subset(calls.day.time, !is.na(calls.day.time$hour))
calls.year.day.time <- calls %>%
  group_by(year, dow, hour) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year', 'dow'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
calls.year.day.time <- subset(calls.year.day.time, !is.na(calls.year.day.time$hour))
calls.year.month <- calls %>%
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
calls.year.month <- subset(calls.year.month, !is.na(calls.year.month$month))

graph <- ggplot(calls.day.time, aes(hour, dow, fill = count)) +
  geom_tile(color = "blue", lwd = .5, linetype = 1) + 
  geom_text(aes(label = count), color = "black", size = 2.5) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "red") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  coord_fixed()

ANALYTICS

Month of Year

Looking at data of calls in Fairfax with the type of call of “SUSPICIOUS” we see clear hot-spots over a per-year and per-month basis. The most common times for these type of calls are in the summer months with peaks usually in July and August. The time of the year with the least activity is in the late fall through winter months with lowest calls usually in November or January. Looking at the data from a year over year perspective, the highest peaks were in 2009 and 2013 with a stable decrease from that point until 2022. 2023 so far looks as though it is on a bit of an increase if the first 4 months of data continue to trend as such. Based on this data, I would expect August to have anywhere from 140-190 calls for suspicious activity.

Day of Week

Looking at our days of week topology we see the trend of highest calls in the summer months with the lowest in the winter months. Next week would be week 28 which lands us right in the center of the graph. This is the time of year with some of the highest trends which means that we should expect 40-50 calls or so in a given week if both the days of the week and months of year data are consistent. Generally the workdays are shown to be slightly higher in calls for suspicious activity with weekends a bit lower on average; the highest overall day is most often Friday. I would expect Monday-Thursday to have anywhere from 4-10 calls, 6-12 for Friday, and 2-8 on Saturday and Sunday.

Hour of Day

The trend for calls in hour of day for suspicious activity are extremely consistent and scale up and down based on the hour of day independent of the day of week. One small thing to note, the highest peaks and lowest valleys come on the weekend days with weekdays still sharing the same hot and cold-spots with just a less gradual difference. In general the highest peaks come from the hours of 11PM through 2AM. A sharp decline then occurs with the lowest point coming at 5-6AM. From this point until the late night peak, a slow incline is shown and these trends are evident in all days of the week.
